    <subsection xml:id="subsec-Forming_Compound_Linear_Inequality_in_one_unkown">
      <title>Forming Compound Linear Inequality in one unkown.</title>

      <activity>

        <p>
          <term>Work in Groups.</term>
        </p>

        <p>

          <ol>

            <li>

              <p>
                Consider <m>x &gt; 1</m> and <m>x &lt; 6.</m>
              </p>

            </li>

            <li>

              <p>
                Make <m>6</m> paper cut-outs and write on each cut-out numbers <m>1</m> to <m>6</m>.
              </p>
            
            </li>
                  
            <li>
              
              <p>
                Arrange the numbers on the cut-outs in an ascending order.
              </p>

            </li>

            <li>

              <p>
                Shade the cutouts that satisfy <m>x &gt; 1</m>.
              </p>

            </li>

            <li>
              
              <p>
                Using the same cut-outs, shade the cut-outs that satisfy <m>x &lt; 6</m>.
              </p> 

            </li>

              <li>

              <p>
                List down the numbers that satisfy <m>x &gt; 1</m> and x &lt; 6.
              </p>

            </li>

          </ol>
          
        </p>
        
      </activity>

      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow> \amp {\color{blue} \text{Learning Point.}} </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        <m>{\color{green} \text{When two simple inequalities are combined, they form a compound inequality.}}</m>
      </p>
      
      <example>

        <statement>

          <p>
            Form a compound inequality for <m>x \lt 8 </m> and <m>x \gt 2</m>.
          </p>
          
        </statement>

        <solution>

          <p>
            <m>x \gt 2</m> is equivalent to <m>2 \lt x</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            By combining <m>2 \lt x</m> and <m>x \lt 8</m>, we obtain the compound inequality.
          </p>

          <p>
            <m>2 \lt x \lt 8</m>.
          </p>

        </solution>

      </example>

      <example>

        <statement>

          <p>
            Form a compound inequality for <m>y \ge 3</m> and <m>y \le 12.</m>
          </p>

        </statement>

        <solution>

            <p>
                <m>y \ge 3</m> can be written as <m>3 \le y</m>.
            </p>

            <p>
                By combining <m>3 \le y</m> and <m>y \le 12</m>, we obtain the compound inequality.
            </p>

            <p>
                Therefore, the compound inequality is <me>3 \le y \le 12</me>.
            </p>

        </solution>

      </example>

